LinkedList

What is a LinkedList?

A LinkedList is a linear data structure where elements aren’t stored in one continuous block (like arrays). Instead, each element (called a node) points to the next one.

Think of it like a chain:

[Data | Next] -> [Data | Next] -> [Data | Next] -> null

In Java:

LinkedList<Integer> list = new LinkedList<>();
🧠 Internal Structure (The Real Mechanics)

Java’s LinkedList is a doubly linked list.

Each node contains:

class Node<E> {
    E item;
    Node<E> next;
    Node<E> prev;
}

So it looks like:

null <- [prev | data | next] <-> [prev | data | next] <-> ... -> null
Why doubly linked?
You can move forward AND backward
Efficient insert/delete at both ends
⚙️ Key Features
1. Dynamic Size

No fixed size like arrays. It grows as needed.

2. Efficient Insert/Delete

Adding/removing elements doesn’t require shifting others.

3. Implements Multiple Interfaces

LinkedList is a hybrid beast:

List
Deque
Queue
Cloneable
Serializable

So it can act like:

List (ordered collection)
Queue (FIFO)
Deque (double-ended queue)
🔑 Key Points (Don’t Ignore These)
Not synchronized (not thread-safe by default)
Allows duplicate elements
Allows null values
Maintains insertion order
Traversal is slower than arrays)


Time Complexity (This is where truth hits)
Operation	Complexity
Access (get)	O(n)
Insert at beginning	O(1)
Insert at end	O(1)
Insert in middle	O(n)
Delete	O(1)*
Search	O(n)
*Deletion is O(1) only if you already have the node reference

Common Methods (Java Collection Framework)
Adding Elements
list.add(10);
list.addFirst(5);
list.addLast(20);